# Cursor Rules — adim-web

## Design
- Always read DESIGN_SYSTEM.md before writing or editing any UI code.
- Never hardcode colors, spacing, radius, or shadow values. Use the tokens/components defined in DESIGN_SYSTEM.md only.
- Never invent a new button, table, modal, or input pattern. If a shared component exists in /src/components/ui/, use it. If it doesn't exist yet, build it there first, matching the reference style in telynx-settings-hub-main, then use it.
- Reference implementation for all visual style: telynx-settings-hub-main. When in doubt about how something should look, check that project's code, not assumptions.

## Scope discipline
- Only touch the files needed for the current task. Do not refactor unrelated pages/components "while you're in there."
- One page or one component per task unless explicitly told to do a multi-page pass.
- Do not change business logic, API calls, or routing when the task is a visual/design task. Flag if a visual fix seems to require a logic change instead of making it silently.

## Workflow
- Before making changes, state in plain terms what you're about to change and which files.
- After making changes, list every file touched and a one-line summary of what changed in each.
- Work on a feature/fix branch, never directly on main.
- Backend changes (FastAPI/Celery/migrations) always go through staging first — never edit production paths directly.

## Output
- No placeholder/lorem content in final UI — use realistic VoxBulk data examples.
- No new npm dependencies without asking first.
